snippet.textDisplay: Hey Doctor Mike I was on one of your other videos that made me look up something. It was like a video that you had posted from like a year ago. But in the video somebody asked you a question about lactose intolerance and you proceeded to say something about the missing missing a key enzyme called lactase that helps them break down the sugar in milk. That kind of set off something in my brain because I'm diabetic. I haven't always been diabetic but it's something that runs in my family. I spent a long time trying to avoid becoming diabetic but unfortunately I was unable to avoid it. I was diagnosed a few years ago during Hurricane Irma. Up until that time I felt fine but that year I just started getting really tired all the time you know couldn't stay awake. But it made me think back because when I was a kid my mom used to force me to drink milk. every time she would make me drink it I would immediately throw it back up. I thought it was personally it was just because I didn't like the taste of milk. But as I got older I found it was really an involuntary response from my body. and then ended up finding out in my Twenties that I was lactose intolerant. I'm just wondering could lactose intolerance be like a warning sign for somebody who hasn't yet been diagnosed with diabetes? I'm Now 37 about to turn 38 in about a week or so and my mom used to make me drink milk when I was like eight nine years old. Just to show a Time progression. could that be a possible early warning sign for somebody who's diabetic?
